<DOC><DOCNO> AP880413-0328 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 2127EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Raytheon     04-13 0314</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Earns-Raytheon,0326</SECOND><HEAD>Raytheon First-Quarter Earnings Rise 11 Percent</HEAD><DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Raytheon Co., one of the nation's topgovernment defense contractors, reported Wednesday that its fiscalfirst-quarter earnings rose more than 11 percent over a year ago.   For the three months ended April 3, Raytheon said net incometotaled $113.3 million, or $1.68 a share, on sales of $1.95billion. That compared with earnings of $101.8 million, or $1.37 ashare, on sales $1.75 billion last year.   Raytheon credited some of the increase to a boost in profitsfrom several divisions, including aircraft and electronics.   The company attributed a 22.6 percent increase in earnings pershare to a drop in the number of shares outstanding due to a stockrepurchase program. Raytheon had 67.3 million shares outstandingduring the first quarter, compared with 74.2 shares outstandingduring the year-ago period.   Raytheon's Wichita, Kan.-based Beech Aircraft Corp. division wasboosted by last year's introduction of the 19-seat Beech 1900turboprop plane, which is being used by several domestic andforeign airlines, said spokesman Larry McCracken.   The electronics division, currently producing air-trafficcontrol radars for the U.S. and Canada, led the company in bothsales and profits, while the energy services division, whichproduces nuclear and non-nuclear power plants, was the only segmentto report a drop in sales.   Raytheon was ranked as the sixth largest defense contractor bythe Department of Defense for fiscal 1987, which ended Sept. 30.The Lexington-based company was ranked seventh the previous fiscalyear, McCracken said.   The backlog of goverment-funded orders, including the five-yearcontract for the Patriot surface-to-air missile, rose from $5.20billion in the first quarter of 1987 to $6.31 billion for the firstquarter this year.   Total orders are presently $8.6 billion, compared to $7.52billion for the first quarter of 1987.   Raytheon non-defense divisions also produce text books, roadconstruction machinery and home appliances.</TEXT></DOC>